To keep Quirn grateful, I also decided to reorganize completely mycontribution to its fame. I scrapped my Joyce seminar which in 1945 hadattracted (if that is the word) only six students--five grim graduates andone not quite normal sophomore. In compensation I added a third lecture inMasterpieces (now including Ulysses) to my weekly quota. The chiefinnovation, however, lay in my bold presentation of knowledge. During myfirst years at Quirn I had accu